Here is a function in JavaScript that takes an array of 5 numbers as input, checks if any of the numbers are prime numbers, and if it finds a prime number, it prints it to the console:

```javascript
function checkForPrimes(arr) {
    let isPrime = false;
    for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
        if (isPrime) {
            console.log(arr[i]);
            break;
        }
        let n = arr[i];
        if (n > 1) {
            for (let j = 2; j < n; j++) {
                if (arr[i] % j === 0) {
                    isPrime = false;
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return isPrime;
}

console.log(checkForPrimes([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])); // true
console.log(checkForPrimes([6, 7, 8, 9, 10])); // true
console.log(checkForPrimes([1, 2, 4, 6, 8])); // false
```

This function checks if any of the numbers in the input array are primes by iterating over each number and checking if it is divisible by any of the other numbers in the array. If it finds a prime number, it returns `true`, and if it doesn't, it returns `false`.

